03:19.358 --> 03:30.471
there'll be somebody who couldn't care less, but 
that's not the usual reaction. I ask that because

03:30.491 --> 03:35.036
one time I was trapped on a plane with Shirley 
MacLaine's advance lady. Oh dear. That was a

03:37.920 --> 03:41.704
difficult four hours.

03:45.278 --> 03:53.367
Well, you know, it's the sort of thing that I'm not 
going to justify astronomy on the basis of all the

03:45.278 --> 03:53.367
things that it does for mankind. It satisfies 
people's curiosity, and I think that's really its

03:53.987 --> 04:00.955
justification. Now, I've been asking this about 
planetary astronomy, but it applies in two other

04:00.975 --> 04:06.100
ways. One is the University of Texas Astronomy 
Department, and astronomers generally in this

04:06.280 --> 04:14.509
country There's no question that McDonald's and 
UT Austin have sold themselves well in this state.

04:19.807 --> 04:25.692
And, well, really, through Stardate, that's what 
people in Boston think of. They never heard. I

04:27.194 --> 04:29.936
don't know if UT has a medical school or a law school 
or anything. Probably don't care that it has a

04:31.237 --> 04:34.420
football team, but they know Stardate. But do you 
think American astronomers have sold as well as

04:36.763 --> 04:43.669
they have in Texas? As well as? What should they be 
doing? I don't know. I mean, this is personal

04:51.881 --> 04:58.468
opinion stuff, but I want to lighten up the book 
with some stuff. I really don't know how to answer

04:58.488 --> 05:00.510
that question. I've been asking everyone, this is 
their one chance, what do you think is the most

05:02.792 --> 05:10.500
important work you've done so far?

05:13.720 --> 05:15.943
They're going to carve something on your 
tombstone.

05:39.657 --> 05:40.318
Well, I... Keeping the astrometry team going 
through all the thick and thin of this problems

05:41.497 --> 05:54.510
that the telescope has had from the very 
beginning, I think, has been important. And

05:54.730 --> 05:56.773
finally starting to get some results. It's been 
the hardest thing that I've ever done, to put it

05:56.813 --> 06:01.537
that way. In terms of ultimate value to science, 
it's hard to say because we've still have our

06:08.412 --> 06:10.054
results to get. If we discover a planet around some 
star, that would be very interesting. That's a

06:19.323 --> 06:24.228
roll

06:19.323 --> 06:24.228
of the dice kind of situation. Some of my earlier 
stuff,

06:25.990 --> 06:37.322
well, I've done some interesting work in 
statistics in connection with the space

06:25.990 --> 06:37.322
telescope work, in fact. We have a very 
interesting computer program, which we

06:37.910 --> 06:52.492
developed, that really makes doing least squares 
problems extremely easy. Oh, well that sounds

06:52.512 --> 06:56.238
like a great boom to mankind. And it's got, there 
have been a lot of people, you know, that have been

06:56.258 --> 07:01.005
using it, and with profit. You can imagine, it's 
got, I mean, you can apply it to all sorts of things.

07:06.901 --> 07:08.824
So I'm kind of proud of that work. And

07:09.184 --> 07:29.576
the other things that have been sort of a 
cumulative thing, I don't know if there's any

07:09.184 --> 07:29.576
particular one paper that I could point to in some 
of my work on celestial mechanics. But taken

07:29.616 --> 07:34.984
together, I think that there's a lot of 
interesting research there. What do you think is

07:36.179 --> 07:47.602
going to happen to planetary astronomy, 
celestial mechanics, that sort of stuff now that

07:36.179 --> 07:47.602
budgets have leveled off or are decreasing? Well, 
